Delayed Flights Exploration¶

by Julia Lee¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

The data that we will be exploring in this notebook is originally from The U.S. Department of Transportation's (DOT) Bureau of Transportation Statistics (BTS) that tracks performance of domestic US flights operated by large air transit companies. There consists of a number of on-time, delayed, cancelled etc. flights that were recorded for the 2008 year.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 1936758 rows and 30 columns in this dataset.

  • Year: 2008
  • Month: 1-12
  • DayofMonth: 1-31
  • DayOfWeek: 1 (Monday) - 7 (Sunday)
  • DepTime: actual departure time (local, hhmm)
  • CRSDepTime: scheduled departure time (local, hhmm)
  • ArrTime: actual arrival time (local, hhmm)
  • CRSArrTime: scheduled arrival time (local, hhmm)
  • UniqueCarrier: unique carrier code
  • FlightNum: flight number
  • TailNum: plane tail number
  • ActualElapsedTime: in minutes
  • CRSElapsedTime: in minutes
  • AirTime: in minutes
  • ArrDelay: arrival delay, in minutes
  • DepDelay: departure delay, in minutes
  • Origin: origin IATA airport code
  • Dest: destination IATA airport code
  • Distance: in miles
  • TaxiIn: taxi in time, in minutes
  • TaxiOut: taxi out time in minutes
  • Cancelled: was the flight cancelled?
  • CancellationCode: reason for cancellation (A = carrier, B = weather, C = NAS, D = security)
  • Diverted: 1 = yes, 0 = no
  • CarrierDelay: in minutes
  • WeatherDelay: in minutes
  • NASDelay: in minutes
  • SecurityDelay: in minutes
  • LateAircraftDelay: in minutes

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Out of the 30 columns, I would like to focus on the time columns (Month, Day, DepTime, ArrTime, etc.) and the Cancelled feature to see if flights were frequently cancelled and why.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I suspect Month, DayofMonth, DayOfWeek, DepTime, ArrTime, Cancelled and ArrDelay columns will be supportive for my investigation.

Before we get into our exploration, I would like to see if we can clean up the data set first. This will help us later with our analysis.

Assess:

  • drop 'Unnamed', 'CRS' columns, 'Taxi in', 'Taxi out', Unique carrier', 'tail number'
  • 'Year', 'Month', 'DayofMonth', 'DayOfWeek' can be datetime
  • 'DepTime', 'ArrTime' can be datetime
  • 'CancellationCode' can be categorical
  • Delay columns need to be integers not floats
  • Actual Elapsed time can be an integer, not a float (minutes)

# Drop unwanted columns

flights = flights.drop('CRSArrTime', axis=1)
flights = flights.drop('TailNum', axis=1)
flights = flights.drop('TaxiIn', axis=1)
flights = flights.drop('TaxiOut', axis=1)

We can now move onto univariate exploration first.

Univariate Exploration¶

To start our exploration, we will take a look at some simple variables of how many flights travelled per month and per day of week to get a sense of the busiest times of the year. We will use a countplot with our x-axis "Month" and "DayOfWeek".

In [99]:
# Countplot of flights per month

plt.figure(figsize = (10,20))
plt.subplot(4, 1, 1)
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
sb.countplot(data = flights, x = 'Month', color = base_color)
plt.title('Flights per Month');

# Countplot of flights per month in descending order

plt.figure(figsize = (10,20))
plt.subplot(4, 1, 2)
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
month_order = flights['Month'].value_counts().index
ax = sb.countplot(data = flights, x = 'Month', color = base_color, order = month_order)
plt.title('Most to Least Flights per Month')

#annotate bars 

for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate('{}'.format(p.get_height()), (p.get_x(), p.get_height()+200));

# Counplot of how many flights per day of week

plt.figure(figsize = (10,20))
plt.subplot(4, 1, 3)
color = sb.color_palette()[1]
sb.countplot(data = flights, x = 'DayOfWeek', color = color)
plt.title('Flights per Weekday')
plt.xlabel('Days of the Week');

# Flights per day of week in descending order 
plt.figure(figsize = (10,20))
plt.subplot(4, 1, 4)
color = sb.color_palette()[1]
day_order = flights['DayOfWeek'].value_counts().index
ax = sb.countplot(data = flights, x = 'DayOfWeek', color = color, order = day_order)
plt.title('Most to Least Flights per Weekday')
plt.xlabel('Days of the Week')

# annotate bars
for p in ax.patches:
    ax.annotate('{}'.format(p.get_height()), (p.get_x()+0.2, p.get_height()+150));

From the simple counplots above, we see that December has the most flights out of the year and Friday sees the most flights out of the week. These results could have been predicted as December is a holiday month where a lot of workers and children/students have a break and many can travel, or many work away from home and go back for the holiday season. Friday is the busiest time of the week as well which can be for similar reasons, as an average Monday-Friday worker would have the weekend off to fly without missing too much work. These are of course all assumptions.

Next to continue on with time, we will see at which hour most flights depart. This might be trickier to sense make because there are other factors that can affect what time a flight departs, and with so many flights from all major airlines, we might not see a trend.

In [115]:
corr_col = ['Distance', 'ArrDelay', 'CarrierDelay', 'WeatherDelay', 'NASDelay', 
            'SecurityDelay', 'LateAircraftDelay', 'ActualElapsedTime' ]

corr = flights[corr_col].corr()

plt.figure(figsize = (8,8))

As to be expected, the delays do not have any significant correlation with each other but all are correlated with arrival delay independently. Actual elapsed time and distance are highly correlated. Let us see if a pair grid can show us any relationship on our numeric variables of choice.

In [116]:
var = ['ActualElapsedTime', 'ArrDelay', 'DepDelay', 'Distance', 'CarrierDelay',
       'WeatherDelay', 'NASDelay', 'SecurityDelay', 'LateAircraftDelay']

# Using a sample of 500 to render plots faster

sample = np.random.choice(flights.shape[0], 500, replace = False)
flights_samp = flights.loc[sample,:]

g = sb.PairGrid(data = flights_samp, vars = var)
g.map_diag(plt.hist, bins = 5)
g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter);

As expected, actual elapsed time and distance are correlated and arrival and departure delays are correlated. As seen in the heat map prior, arrival and departure delays are positively correlated with the different types of delays.

Surprisingly, NAS delays are positively correlated with actual elapsed time, distance, arrival delay and departure delay. Delays from the NAS (National Airspace System) comprise of non extreme weahter conditions, high volume traffic and traffic control delays.

Let us hone in on all the types of delays and arrival delay as we might be able to see a highly correlated result. Security Delay will be ommited as a high correlation was not reflected in the Pair Grid above and will increase data to ink ratio, making the plot easier to read.
